elements.2211.03192_8f7e50e72bbcf429a42896b035308: Visual analysis is central to gaining insight on the underlying behaviour of unsteady flow data
elements.2211.03192_a4ced1d452ca87b04c86738e544e9: Numerous visualization techniques have been developed to extract meaningful information from flow data, all in support of analyzing a variety of flow features
elements.2211.03192_3d71f501965c0314cd64c941f717d: Among these techniques, notable ones include the finite-time Lyapunov exponents (FTLE)
elements.2211.03192_e7b122ea06d8c57973010ab4cff5e: , used to understand the rate of separation between nearby particles integrated over a finite time interval, and its resulting Lagrangian coherent structures (LCS)
elements.2211.03192_d5cae6017382e49c39f00b3c7394d: , extracted as the ridges of the FTLE field
elements.2211.03192_5a98930cb10d11cd6c3de930aa2e0: Streaklines are another visualization technique widely used by researchers, used to factor out background motion in flows, and identify underlying vortices that might be present
elements.2211.03192_723dc419b5ef7208ed6458b39c288: Other flow visualization techniques include line integral convolution (LIC)
elements.2211.03192_0d5011eaa82b41b0bafb59314ec4f: A core component common to all the above techniques is the computation of the flow map
elements.2211.03192_1d22f03558c4a9d6cb2768313cea2: The flow map provides the position of a particle advected under a flow over a finite time span, and typically, this is computed by integrating a time-varying vector field
elements.2211.03192_cdb3844ab83202b66b275fc7ce225: For large time spans, this integration process can become computationally expensive, and thus impede interactivity within visual analysis
elements.2211.03192_17a37db65f3472cf6cd134f46d313: For example, trajectories of a dense set of particles sufficiently covering the spatial domain must be computed in order to generate the FTLE field
elements.2211.03192_9531e4d54d028296ac9dfc321ac40: If the user is interested in interactively exploring FTLE under varying time spans, the expense in computing the flow map can hinder this exploration
elements.2211.03192_b600ba0dbd5123d0aab022a0c754b: Techniques that can improve the flow map computation time are thus attractive for a wide-variety of downstream visualization tasks
elements.2211.03192_36bf5bfd2bbfd9f08195469479440: In the literature, numerous techniques have been proposed for fast FTLE computation
elements.2211.03192_1ca8dc9514f56fb0d9a4935399b56: Most of the these techniques fall into the general category of reducing the number of flow map evaluations required to accurately estimate the FTLE field
elements.2211.03192_2b5835c847eb96ea6ac66d32ca4ab: In a similar way, many other techniques have been proposed for fast LIC computation
elements.2211.03192_86ff1c758dc40a3a6beb282a80112: However, most of these techniques are targeted towards improving the computation time of a specific downstream visualization task
elements.2211.03192_4ca34dd2aeac08f71028277388320: For the majority of flow visualization techniques, the flow map computation time acts as a bottleneck, and few techniques have focused on the core of the problem i.e. improving the flow map computation time
elements.2211.03192_ae8b55f86d02b2d7b5f08d2a51564: Motivated by these problems, in this we work we propose a novel technique for fast and accurate flow map computation
elements.2211.03192_599b154c02d1a1055b73ecd7fca1b: We propose a novel coordinate-based neural network that serves as a surrogate for a flow map
elements.2211.03192_b228284281c4f932014eb69b65940: Specifically, given a particle identified by a spatiotemporal coordinate, and time span, the network predicts the spatial position corresponding to the particle's integration under the flow field
elements.2211.03192_13298aeb7e3f2529b9e6dbe48614d: Such neural representations of flow maps have been recently studied, both for 2D unsteady flows
elements.2211.03192_7e41defd753354a69315002069329: , and more broadly for learning latent space representations
elements.2211.03192_c8bbad55c9771867f637678b64d0f: However, the learning of flow maps presents a number of challenges for existing methods
elements.2211.03192_002007f9a74ee995b8732f9235b90: First, there is a steep training data requirement, where it is necessary to generate a large number of flow map samples on which to learn
elements.2211.03192_762816f1debd2caf4b358517d8bd9: Second, the input dimensionality varies over space, time, and time span, and thus in order to match the high dimensionality of the input space, the complexity (e.g. number of parameters) of the network often needs to be quite large
elements.2211.03192_af1596e9ce57d80e8a977ebf0bf4f: The complexity of the network can prove prohibitively expensive for training, provided the large dataset size, as well as prevent interactivity for use in downstream visual analysis
elements.2211.03192_e9f377411535ed06cef6ff4dd4e43: Our approach aims to address, at once, these challenges through a novel network design that enables efficient inference, coupled with a novel optimization scheme for scalable training
elements.2211.03192_3cc2458bcf99902c2777f6ff54aa9: A key aspect of our approach is that, through careful network design and optimization, we eliminate the need to learn from ground-truth flow map samples altogether
elements.2211.03192_45238fafd3583c74c0e5c4e3c797e: Rather, we take advantage of a basic property of flow maps: the instantaneous velocity of the flow map should be equivalent to the vector field
elements.2211.03192_c7581ef6ef0374f390fd336cba04b: By optimizing the flow map derivative to represent the vector field, this
elements.2211.03192_b8c4cd82ba02e73e72eaac3ed5492: the flow map itself to give a good approximation of particle transport, under small time spans
elements.2211.03192_bc1b468d89a565e4a4a2c97f8244e: We show how to leverage this in devising a self-consistency criterion for learning the flow map under a range of time spans
elements.2211.03192_846c51af4d168bf5dc46aeea7f75f: Moreover, building on recent hybrid grid-MLP models
elements.2211.03192_a978902194acb31abba4480fac33b: , our network is efficient to evaluate, which enables both scalable training, as well as efficient inference
elements.2211.03192_5741d012bcbad95c096d5869a1c90: Our implementation can be found here :
elements.2211.03192_3a2dc20ddcdd46ea308a457de8ef6: Our main contributions can be summarized as follows:
elements.2211.03192_c1186c452444a60e39160ec40945f: We propose a novel network architecture for learning a neural representation of flow maps, that is fast, accurate and scalable.
elements.2211.03192_f4ae19c247a95ac27ccac569704d4: We propose a novel way to optimize the network only using the vector field, without requiring access to flow map samples during optimization.
elements.2211.03192_0f50f845f08ef4265f62de3469ccf: We show the advantage of using our technique by comparing against existing techniques both qualitatively and quantitatively
elements.2211.03192_8e13ebbd1024e4a2d18d31f1cbf5c: We demonstrate that, with modest training time, our method provides for a more accurate flow map approximation, and is more efficient at inference time, and hence applicable to numerous unsteady flow visualization techniques.
